{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CNQoMK9vpwtz1Ad8QVPf6c","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→FROM maven:3.9.12-ibm-semeru-21-noble AS builder\n     2→\n     3→WORKDIR /app\n     4→COPY pom.xml .\n     5→COPY src ./src\n     6→\n     7→RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests\n     8→\n     9→# ---- Runtime Stage ----\n    10→FROM icr.io/appcafe/open-liberty:full-java17-openj9-ubi\n    11→\n    12→USER root\n    13→\n    14→# UBI uses yum\n    15→RUN yum install -y python3 python3-pip curl \\\n    16→    && yum clean all\n    17→\n    18→# Install requests for smoke tests\n    19→RUN pip3 install requests\n    20→\n    21→# Shared browsers path so Chromium is cached once\n    22→ENV PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH=/ms-playwright\n    23→RUN mkdir -p /ms-playwright && chmod 755 /ms-playwright\n    24→\n    25→# Install playwright (allow failure since it's optional for smoke tests)\n    26→RUN pip3 install playwright==1.47.0 pytest \\\n    27→    && playwright install --with-deps chromium || true\n    28→\n    29→# Copy Liberty config\n    30→COPY --chown=1001:0 src/main/liberty/config/server.xml /config/server.xml\n    31→\n    32→# Copy H2 driver jar to Liberty lib dir\n    33→RUN mkdir -p /config/lib\n    34→COPY --from=builder --chown=1001:0 /root/.m2/repository/com/h2database/h2/2.2.224/h2-2.2.224.jar /config/lib/h2-2.2.224.jar\n    35→\n    36→# Copy the WAR\n    37→COPY --from=builder --chown=1001:0 /app/target/order-jakarta.war /config/apps/order-jakarta.war\n    38→\n    39→# Copy smoke test file\n    40→COPY smoke.py /app/smoke.py\n    41→RUN chmod +x /app/smoke.py\n    42→\n    43→EXPOSE 8080 9443\n    44→\n    45→CMD [\"/opt/ol/wlp/bin/server\", \"run\", \"defaultServer\"]\n    46→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c75ef7e1-cdcb-4fc9-ba4d-53d982e17ac3","uuid":"26cf70b6-6451-46f9-9cc8-4863723a3cf8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_017vmnQnNzjfbLDkbkKmNyrR","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\"  xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n     2→         xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n     3→  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>\n     4→\n     5→  <groupId>example</groupId>\n     6→  <artifactId>order-jakarta</artifactId>\n     7→  <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>\n     8→  <name>order-jakarta</name>\n     9→  <packaging>war</packaging>\n    10→\n    11→  <properties>\n    12→    <java.version>17</java.version>\n    13→    <maven.compiler.source>17</maven.compiler.source>\n    14→    <maven.compiler.target>17</maven.compiler.target>\n    15→    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>\n    16→    <liberty.var.default.http.port>8080</liberty.var.default.http.port>\n    17→    <liberty.var.app.context.root>/</liberty.var.app.context.root>\n    18→  </properties>\n    19→\n    20→  <dependencies>\n    21→    <!-- Jakarta EE 10 API -->\n    22→    <dependency>\n    23→      <groupId>jakarta.platform</groupId>\n    24→      <artifactId>jakarta.jakartaee-api</artifactId>\n    25→      <version>10.0.0</version>\n    26→      <scope>provided</scope>\n    27→    </dependency>\n    28→\n    29→    <!-- H2 Database -->\n    30→    <dependency>\n    31→      <groupId>com.h2database</groupId>\n    32→      <artifactId>h2</artifactId>\n    33→      <version>2.2.224</version>\n    34→    </dependency>\n    35→\n    36→    <!-- PrimeFaces -->\n    37→    <dependency>\n    38→      <groupId>org.primefaces</groupId>\n    39→      <artifactId>primefaces</artifactId>\n    40→      <version>14.0.0</version>\n    41→      <classifier>jakarta</classifier>\n    42→    </dependency>\n    43→  </dependencies>\n    44→\n    45→  <build>\n    46→    <finalName>order-jakarta</finalName>\n    47→    <plugins>\n    48→      <plugin>\n    49→        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\n    50→        <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>\n    51→        <version>3.11.0</version>\n    52→        <configuration>\n    53→          <source>17</source>\n    54→          <target>17</target>\n    55→        </configuration>\n    56→      </plugin>\n    57→      <plugin>\n    58→        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\n    59→        <artifactId>maven-war-plugin</artifactId>\n    60→        <version>3.4.0</version>\n    61→      </plugin>\n    62→      <plugin>\n    63→        <groupId>io.openliberty.tools</groupId>\n    64→        <artifactId>liberty-maven-plugin</artifactId>\n    65→        <version>3.10</version>\n    66→      </plugin>\n    67→    </plugins>\n    68→  </build>\n    69→</project>\n    70→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c75ef7e1-cdcb-4fc9-ba4d-53d982e17ac3","uuid":"a9cc444e-aac4-419a-a5ab-2444c84aeb5c"}
